<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-117-035 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 214 443</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lasers andamp; Optronics  July 1991 v10 n7 p14(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Silicon emits light, excites researchers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hecht, Jeff.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Researchers at the UK's Royal Signals and Radar Establishment showthat deeply etched silicon faces emit red light when illuminatedby an argon laser beam.andP;  Silicon does not work with conventionallight-emitting diodes or diode lasers because it has an indirectbandgap.andP;  Nonetheless, researchers can produce green, yellow, andorange emission in optically excited samples.andP;  No one is exactlycertain how the light emission functions, but the process involvescolumns so small that they cause quantum confinement of currentcarriers acting as quantum wires.andP;  Electron-hole pairs are createdby laser illumination of the columns and the pairs re-combine andemit a lower-energy photon.andP;  Smaller columns mean less energyloss.andP;  British and French teams are now working on methods toelectrically power the etched silicon emitters.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Light-Emitting DiodesLasersMaterials AnalysisScientific Research.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>